You can't make an entire DOM tree truly "read-only," but you can prevent modifications to the tree using various approaches:

1. **Event Prevention**: You can prevent modifications through event listeners:
   ```javascript
   document.addEventListener('DOMNodeInserted', (e) => e.stopImmediatePropagation(), true);
   document.addEventListener('DOMNodeRemoved', (e) => e.stopImmediatePropagation(), true);
   ```

2. **Mutation Observers**: Use Mutation Observers to revert any changes immediately:
   ```javascript
   const observer = new MutationObserver((mutations) => {
       mutations.forEach((mutation) => {
           mutation.target.remove(); // Revert changes
       });
   });

   observer.observe(document.body, { childList: true, subtree: true });
   ```

While you can implement such mechanisms, determined users can always manipulate the DOM using developer tools.

You can make a whole DOM element "read-only" in the sense that you prevent editing its content, but you can’t technically make it completely immutable due to the nature of how the DOM works. However, you can prevent modifications by intercepting any attempts to alter its content. Here's an example using a `MutationObserver`:

```javascript
const element = document.getElementById("myElement");

// Create a Mutation Observer to track changes
const observer = new MutationObserver((mutations) => {
    mutations.forEach((mutation) => {
        // Revert changes (for example, by restoring original HTML)
        element.innerHTML = element.dataset.originalContent;
    });
});

// Store the original content in a data attribute
element.dataset.originalContent = element.innerHTML;

// Start observing for changes in child elements
observer.observe(element, { childList: true, subtree: true });

// Example of trying to change the content
setTimeout(() => {
    element.innerHTML = "New Content"; // This will be reverted
}, 2000);
```

In this snippet, the `MutationObserver` listens for changes and reverts any modification to the original content. This effectively makes the element read-only in terms of its displayed content.

In Flutter, you can achieve this by using a `HookWidget` and implementing the `didChangeAppLifecycleState` method. This method is called whenever the app lifecycle changes, such as when a page is shown or navigated to.

Here's an example of how to use `HookWidget` to perform some work when a page is shown:
```dart
import 'package:flutter/widgets/widget.dart';

class MyHookWidget extends HookWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return ProviderScope(
      child: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(title: Text('My App')),
        body: Center(child: ElevatedButton(
          child: Text('Click Me'),
          onPressed: () {
            // Perform some work here when the button is pressed
          },
        )),
      ),
    );
  }

  @override
  void didChangeAppLifecycleState(AppLifecycleState state) {
    super.didChangeAppLifecycleState(state);

    if (state == AppLifecycleState.resumed) {
      // Perform some work here when the app resumes, such as initializing variables or fetching data
    }
  }
}
```
